Reporting period

The data presented in this section refers only to the user-defined period: 01 Jan 2009 - 31 Dec 2009. Cohorts of women who were admitted or delivered during this period are presented separately. Reference is made to cohorts from the 12 months prior to 31 December 2009 and the full programme to allow quick comparisons.

Definition

Tab & Variable Definition
Table The Table tab shows the number and percentage of patients included in your cohort by calendar month.
    Month Calendar month and patients with missing inclusion dates.
    Previous 12 months This column represents all patients included in the cohort in the 365 days before the end of user-defined reporting period. The month containing the end of reporting date will therefore be split between two years of inclusion.

For example, if the end of reporting date is chosen as 15 January 2020, in the table January will represent the number of patients included from 16 January 2019 to 31 January 2019 plus from 1 January 2020 to 15 January 2020.
    Full programme This describes all patients entering the cohort prior to the user-defined end of reporting date.
Monthly initiations The Monthly initiations tab graphically represents cohort inclusion during the previous 12 months. Inclusion is restricted by the end of the user-defined reporting period as mentioend in the plot subtitle. The month containing the end of reporting date is coloured red for emphasis. The start of reporting date is not used to generate this graph.
Quarterly initiations The Quarterly initiations tab depicts cohort inclusions by quarter to provide a longer historical overview. Inclusion is restricted by the end of the user-defined reporting period as mentioend in the plot subtitle. The start of reporting date is not used to generate this graph.

Plot

Definition

Early Infant Diagnosis should be performed before 12 weeks of life using an age-appropriate test. This table includes infants that were born more than 12 weeks prior to 31 December 2009.

Variable Definition
EID performed This is a process indicator which establishes the proportion of all live births who were tested for HIV prior to 12 weeks of age. The indicator requires an HIV assessment date within 12 weeks of birth with a molecular HIV test type being recorded. A record of an HIV test result is not required for this indicator.
EID results This quality indicator describes the proportion of infants tested who had a positive result. Indeterminate, unknown or unavailable results are recorded as missing.

Definition

The PMTCT programme outcome is given 18 months after delivery to allow sufficient time for infants to be tested for HIV using an antigen/antibody test. Infants may continue to be exposed to HIV through breastfeeding, but for convenience of reporting, outcomes are attributed 18 months after delivery.

This table includes infants that were born more than 18 months prior to 31 December 2009.

Variable Definition
Infant final HIV status The final HIV test result recorded for each infant.
Final programme outcome The final programme outcome recorded for each infant.
